<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1901-01-07T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1901-01-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="189" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d189">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hill</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Choate</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1901-01-07"><hi rend="italic">January 7,
                                1901</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 526.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: In view of representations made to the
                            Department by the American Presbyterian Kongo Mission of their need of
                            having some one whom they can consult in matters arising between the
                            mission and the Government of the Kongo Free State, it is desired to
                            have you make known to the British Government the gratification which
                            this Government would experience in learning that the British consul at
                            Boma had been authorized to take care of American interests in the Kongo
                            Free State until United States consular representation there is provided
                            for by Congressional action.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">David J. Hill</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Acting Secretary.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>